# Step 4: Docker Compose

Create:

```text
docker-compose.yml
```

```yaml
services:

  kafka:

    image: apache/kafka:latest

    container_name: kafka

    ports:
      - "9092:9092"

    environment:
      KAFKA_NODE_ID: 1

      KAFKA_PROCESS_ROLES: broker,controller

      KAFKA_LISTENERS: PLAINTEXT://:9092,CONTROLLER://:9093

      KAFKA_ADVERTISED_LISTENERS: PLAINTEXT://localhost:9092

      KAFKA_CONTROLLER_LISTENER_NAMES: CONTROLLER

      KAFKA_LISTENER_SECURITY_PROTOCOL_MAP: CONTROLLER:PLAINTEXT,PLAINTEXT:PLAINTEXT

      KAFKA_CONTROLLER_QUORUM_VOTERS: 1@localhost:9093

      KAFKA_OFFSETS_TOPIC_REPLICATION_FACTOR: 1
```

---
 
## Image

```yaml
image: apache/kafka:latest
```

Docker downloads the official Kafka image.

Think of it as downloading a virtual machine with Kafka pre-installed.

---

## Container Name

```yaml
container_name: kafka
```

Instead of:

```text
kafka_8fhs92
```

You'll simply see:

```text
kafka
```

---

## Ports

```yaml
9092:9092
```

Meaning:

```text
Your Computer

↓

localhost:9092

↓

Kafka Container

↓

9092
```

Spring Boot will connect using:

```properties
spring.kafka.bootstrap-servers=localhost:9092
```

---

## Node ID

```yaml
KAFKA_NODE_ID=1
```

Every broker has a unique ID.

Development:

```text
Broker 1
```

Production:

```text
Broker 1

Broker 2

Broker 3
```

---

## Process Roles

```yaml
broker,controller
```

This broker performs two jobs:

* Broker
* Controller

Production usually separates these roles for larger clusters.

---

## Listeners

```yaml
PLAINTEXT://:9092
```

This tells Kafka:

> Listen for client connections on port 9092.

Spring Boot Producer will connect here.

---

## Advertised Listener

```yaml
localhost:9092
```

When clients ask Kafka:

> "How do I reach you?"

Kafka replies:

```text
localhost:9092
```

This setting is critical. A wrong value is one of the most common reasons developers cannot connect to Kafka.

